(36, 1, '2020-06-10 22:27:12', '2020-06-10 20:27:12', '<h3 style=\"font-size: 1.875rem; line-height: 2.125rem; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0.625rem; margin-left: 0px; font-family: GeographEditWeb, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif !important;\">30 Days of Hope: Stories of Biodiversity, Balance, and Restoration</h3>\n<h3>As we cap off the #30DaysofHope on this the International Day for Biological Diversity, we can’t help but reflect on the interconnectedness of our world and the need to work together to safeguard our collective future. We hope the stories we’ve shared over the last month have uplifted you, and that you will continue to find inspiration in nature. Read on to catch up on all the positive stories we’ve shared this week.</h3>\n<p>										<img width=\"640\" height=\"253\" src=\"http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1-1024x404.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1-1024x404.jpg 1024w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1-300x118.jpg 300w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1-768x303.jpg 768w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1-850x336.jpg 850w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Roumania_credit-Victoria-Hllman_ccMN_2348680_sml-1140x450-1.jpg 1140w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"></p>\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Female European brown bear looking for food on the forest floor with her single cub (out of shot). Photograph by Victoria Hillman, National Geographic.May 22, 2020</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today, on the International Day for Biological Diversity, we draw the 30 Days of Hope to a close. Together with the Wyss Foundation’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.campaignfornature.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Campaign for Nature</a>, we’ve shared a story of the hope and strength found in nature every day for the past 30 days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In that time, we’ve traveled virtually around the globe, checking in on rhino reintroduction at Malawi’s Majete Wildlife Reserve, honoring the voices of indigenous peoples and local communities in conservation in Canada, rewilding Europe’s Danube Delta through the removal of obsolete dams, and making many other stops along the way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we look back, we can’t help but reflect on the interconnectedness of our world, and the need to work together to safeguard our collective future. We know that in places where biodiversity and ecosystems have been depleted, they have the capacity to come back. Join us in taking some extra time today to celebrate the richness of nature and the people, organizations, and countries working to protect it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for coming along on this journey. Catch up on all of our inspirational stories from the past 30 days here:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2020/05/01/campaign-for-nature-bring-you-30-days-of-hope-on-social/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">week 1</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2020/05/08/30-days-of-hope-inspirational-nature-stories-from-africa-canada-australia-and-china/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">week 2</a>, and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2020/05/15/30-days-of-hope-stories-of-nature-resilience-in-the-sea-and-on-land/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">week 3</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Uplifting News on Endangered Species Day</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":215754} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/11_Guina_credit-Joel-Sartore-National-Geographic-Photo-Ark_2750748-720x480.jpg\" alt=\"Güiña posing for the camera\" class=\"wp-image-215754\"/><figcaption>Güiña, Leopardus guigna tigriillo, at Fauna Andina in Santiago, Chile. Photograph by Joel Sartore, National Geographic, PhotoArk.</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the UN’s Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services was released in May 2019, it stated that there are&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2019/05/ipbes-un-biodiversity-report-warns-one-million-species-at-risk/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">nearly 1 million species currently under threat of extinction</a>. But the extinction crisis isn’t new: 15 years ago, in the face of this threat, National Geographic Fellow and photographer, Joel Sartore made it his mission to record our planet’s biodiversity. His&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.nationalgeographic.org/projects/photo-ark/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Photo Ark</a>&nbsp;project captures images of species ranging from the everyday (domestic rats) to the most at risk (like the critically endangered Sumatran rhino). His work is a powerful testament to the importance of protecting the weird and wonderful species that make our planet unique.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And now, Joel has added the 10,000th species to the National Geographic Photo Ark! Meet the güiña: The smallest wildcat in the Americas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Balancing the Needs of Humanity and the Planet in Amsterdam</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":215755} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Amsterdam_Netherlands_credit-George-Steinmetz_cc6CN_2180949_sml-720x480.jpg\" alt=\"Aerial landscape of coastal homes and agricultural fields just north of Amsterdam \" class=\"wp-image-215755\"/><figcaption>Village and vacation homes are strung along the southwest side of the Ijselmeer inland sea just north of Amsterdam. Photograph by George Steinmetz, National Geographic.</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Last month, Amsterdam announced it would formally embrace the “doughnut” economic model, an ambitious plan that seeks to balance the needs of humanity with that of the planet. It is the first city in the world to use this circular economy model to guide public policy decisions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the model, the doughnut’s inner ring outlines a basic social foundation, based on the UN’s sustainable development goals. It includes necessities like clean water, housing, gender equality, work, and education. The doughnut’s outer ring represents an ecological ceiling for planetary health that avoids damaging the climate, soils, oceans, and biodiversity. Together, this model aims to create a balanced economy that meets immediate needs while looking to the future.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Discover', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'discover', '', '', '2020-06-11 01:57:50', '2020-06-10 23:57:50', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wp/?page_id=36', 0, 'page', '', 0),
